"""
rel_vref — Algorithm 2: fixed 7-entry Vref retry table + ROR-lite (Retention
Optimized Reading) per-block calibration cache.

Contract: doc/05_design/hardware/nand_recovery/recovery_algorithms_design.md §3
(design §9 lane L3, depends on L1 `rel_types.spl` only). Taxonomy lineage:
doc/01_research/hardware/nand_recovery/nand_ssd_recovery_prevention_taxonomy.md
§2.1 (table-based / fixed read retry — the 7-entry table) + §2.2 ROR (learn the
block's optimal read-reference voltage and reuse it on subsequent reads).

This is a PURE-POLICY LEAF (design §0 / architecture §0 LAW): imports ONLY
`nvme_types.*` + `nd_types.*` + `rel_types.*` — never `fil`/`ftl` — so both
`fil.spl` and `ftl.spl` may import this module without a cycle. No handle is
held here; every fn is a free function over `RelVrefCache` (return-the-object,
value-type array law) or a stateless table lookup.

Typed-dimensions law (guide "TYPED DIMENSIONS LAW"): `blk` parameters are
`NdBlock` (not raw i64) here, matching `RelLadderState.blk`/`RelBlockObs.blk`
in rel_types.spl — L4 (`rel_ladder.spl`) holds `st.blk: NdBlock` and passes it
straight through to `rel_vref_lookup`/`rel_vref_calibrate` with no conversion.
The dense `RelVrefCache.offset/valid/gen` arrays stay `[i64]` (design §1.3):
`blk.idx` is the flat array index; the design's literal pseudocode signatures
(`blk: i64`) are followed at that ARRAY-INDEXING granularity, not at the
public fn-parameter granularity, per the typed-dims law's "convert at the flat
boundary" rule (rel_types.spl's own header comment for L4 makes the same
choice).

Retry-table order and calibration/decay pseudocode below are copied verbatim
from the design (§3) — this lane does not redesign them. `rel_vref_lookup`
returning 0 on an uncalibrated block is the "no seed" signal the L4 ladder's
calibrated-seed-first rung (design §2, rung 1) is built on: `seed == 0` is
exactly the condition under which the ladder falls through to
`rel_vref_table_at(0)` as its first retry offset — so table[0] is the de facto
seed for a never-calibrated block, one hop away from `rel_vref_lookup` itself.

Bounds hardening (guide "NVMe fw hardening bar" — no unchecked bounds, no
silent fail-open): `blk.idx` is validated with `nvme_types.block_in_range`
before any array access (mirrors the existing `fil.read` out-of-range guard
exercised in rel_seams_check.spl); an out-of-range block fails closed (lookup
returns 0 = "no seed", calibrate/decay are no-ops that return the cache
unchanged) rather than indexing out of bounds. `off` is clamped to
`[-REL_VREF_MAX_ABS, REL_VREF_MAX_ABS]` in `rel_vref_calibrate` before it is
persisted — the table itself never emits an out-of-range offset, but a
defensive clamp keeps the invariant true even if a future caller (or a bug in
L4) hands in something else; the constant IS the design's own §3 rationale
("keeps vref = 128±32 inside the 0..255 code range with headroom"), not an
invented one.
"""

use nvme_types.*
use nd_types.*
use rel_types.*

# ── Fixed 7-entry retry table (design §3, fn-returning literal — freestanding-
# safe, no module-level collection init). Retention-biased order: retention
# charge loss shifts the programmed lobe DOWN (ne_retention_delta is
# negative-only for vt>128) so negative offsets dominate; disturb shifts UP so
# positive offsets are interleaved to also cover that secondary case within
# the 7-step budget. ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
fn rel_vref_table_len() -> i64:
    7

fn rel_vref_table_at(i: i64) -> i64:
    if i == 0: return 0 - 8
    if i == 1: return 0 - 16
    if i == 2: return 8
    if i == 3: return 0 - 24
    if i == 4: return 16
    if i == 5: return 0 - 32
    if i == 6: return 24
    0

# Table max |offset| (design §3 constants table): keeps vref = 128±32 inside
# the 0..255 sense-reference code range with headroom. Also the calibration
# clamp bound below.
val REL_VREF_MAX_ABS: i64 = 32

fn rel_vref_clamp_offset(off: i64) -> i64:
    if off > REL_VREF_MAX_ABS:
        return REL_VREF_MAX_ABS
    if off < 0 - REL_VREF_MAX_ABS:
        return 0 - REL_VREF_MAX_ABS
    off

# ── ROR-lite per-block calibration cache (design §3 decision/mutator fns) ─────
# Calibrated-seed-first lookup: valid==1 means a prior read on this block
# recovered at `offset` (a CalibrateBlock verdict persisted it); 0 means "no
# seed" and the L4 ladder falls to the fixed table starting at index 0.
fn rel_vref_lookup(c: RelVrefCache, blk: NdBlock) -> i64:
    if not block_in_range(blk.idx):
        return 0                                # fail closed: no seed, never OOB-index
    if c.valid[blk.idx] == 1:
        return c.offset[blk.idx]
    0                                            # 0 = "no seed", ladder falls to table

# Persist the winning offset post-success (ROR) — return-the-object mutator.
fn rel_vref_calibrate(c: RelVrefCache, blk: NdBlock, off: i64) -> RelVrefCache:
    var out = c
    if not block_in_range(blk.idx):
        return out                               # fail closed: unchanged, never OOB-write
    out.offset[blk.idx] = rel_vref_clamp_offset(off)
    out.valid[blk.idx] = 1
    out

# Erased block: retention offset is void — decay exactly that block's entry so
# a recycled block never reuses a stale retention-drift calibration.
fn rel_vref_decay_on_erase(c: RelVrefCache, blk: NdBlock) -> RelVrefCache:
    var out = c
    if not block_in_range(blk.idx):
        return out                               # fail closed: unchanged, never OOB-write
    out.valid[blk.idx] = 0
    out.offset[blk.idx] = 0
    out
